0.body: Cred is a simple and secure CLI tool for managing passwords (pass) and environment variables (env) using Go. It encrypts sensitive information using GPG keys , ensuring safe storage and retrieval.
0.breadcrumbs: Introduction Â» Introduction to Cred CLI
0.title: Introduction to Cred CLI

1.body: Password Management (cred pass) : Store, retrieve, and manage passwords securely. Environment Variable Management (cred env) : Store encrypted .env files and retrieve values on demand. GPG Encryption : Uses GNU Privacy Guard (GPG) to encrypt credentials. Simple CLI Interface : Easy-to-use commands for adding, viewing, and modifying stored credentials. Cross-Platform Support : Works on Linux, macOS, and Windows.

102.body: Generate the autocompletion script for the bash shell. This script depends on the 'bash-completion' package. If it is not installed already, you can install it via your OS's package manager. To load completions in your current shell session: source <(cred completion bash) To load completions for every new session, execute once: Linux: cred completion bash > /etc/bash_completion.d/cred macOS: cred completion bash > $(brew --prefix)/etc/bash_completion.d/cred You will need to start a new shell for this setup to take effect. cred completion bash

19.body: Each configuration entry must be on a new line. Each line is split into key and value by "=". Whitespace around keys and values is allowed and will be trimmed automatically. Duplicate keys are allowed; the last occurrence will overwrite previous values. Lines starting with # are treated as comments and ignored by the parser. Invalid config will be ignored by the parser.

21.title: cred

22.body: Cred is a powerful CLI tool built in Go for managing passwords and environment variables. It uses GPG encryption to securely store and manage sensitive information. Examples and usage: Initialize with a GPG key: cred init Store a new credentials: cred {pass/env} insert Retrieve a credentials: cred {pass/env} show Retrieve a credentials: cred {pass/env} copy List all stored credentials: cred {pass/env} list
22.title: Synopsis

70.body: The generate command creates a new password of specified length and stores it securely in the password store. You can specify the length of the password using the -l flag.
